                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">814.00/1036: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Whitehouse</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-12-30T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 30, 1930—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>82. Your 129, December 29, 12 noon. In the absence of immediate danger to
                    American lives and property or other very compelling motives, the Department
                    considers it to be inadvisable to dispatch a war vessel to Guatemala at this
                    time. The Department is following the situation with the greatest concern and in
                    order to be in readiness <pb facs="0286" n="192" xml:id="pg_192"/> it desires to
                    receive full and timely reports of all developments, together with such further
                    recommendations as you may judge necessary.</p>
                <p>Also, the Department desires you to telegraph a statement of the American
                    citizens and the American interests which may be endangered by civil
                    disturbances.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
